{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060866A/1957121001/1054.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAR, Washington, 0. C.\nTvtsnsv- nsrtMwta it. last _________\nA-4\nPARTIAL TEXT OF SPEECH\nEisenhower's Mind\nKeen, Adams Says\nl The following is a partial text of a speech by ,1\nPresidential Assistant Sherman Adams, delivered at\na Republican finance dinner in St. Louis last night:\nNow. (or the next (ew min\nutes. I thought you would be\ninterested in whet happens\nwhen a President suddenly be\ncomes ill. Always, at a time like\nthis, attention is again drawn\nto the problems ol administer\ning! the Government in the\nevent the Present should be\ncome incapacitated There has\nbeen some chatter about usur\npation of powers by myself or\nothers on the Presidents staff.\nThere has been a good dral of\nmisleading claptrap about the\nactivities of the Vice President.\nIn my book he has performed\nadmirably these past two weeks\nanj on the previous occasions\nwhen the President has been\ntaleen ill. Let s go back over\nthe sequence of events In this\nrecent illness.\nEvents as Illness\nThe first indication that the\nPresident was Indisposed was\nhis own statement of feeling\nchilled after returning from the\nWashington airport, where he\nwrit to meet officially the head\nof a foreign state. He had to\nstand in the cold for a con\nsiderable time When he re\nturned to his office, 4us personal\nsecretary noticed a speech dif\nficulty. This she at once com\nmunicated to me and to the\nsecretary of the President's\nstaff Almost coincidentally, the\nPresident remarked that he still\nfelt chilled He thereupon went\nto the White House and went\nto bed\nThe doctor was called at\nonce. In turn the President's\ndoctor in consultation with\nother doctors diagnosed that\nthe President had sustained\nwhat people commonly call a\nminor stroke\u2014a term doctors\navoid unless the impairment is\nfar more serious than the Pres\nident\u2019s was. In medical terms,\nas I understand them, the word\n\u2022'stroke\" is used only when\nthere is a paralysis or a\nhemorrhage, or both. The Pres\nident had neither.\nMeanwhile, on the business\nside of the White House, a lot\nof things were going on\nI at once telephoned the Vice\nPresident and advised him of\nthe President's illness: The\nsame message was communi\ncated to various members of\nthe President's Cabinet. Key\nmembers of the White House\nstaffs were notified. Meetings\nwere quickly arranged with\neight or ten of this group in\norder to reschedule everts\nplanned for the President's per\nsonal participation.\nBusy Time of Tear\nI need hardly to remind this\naudience that at this particular\ntime of year the burdens of the\nPresidency are at their heav\niest. This is the time for com\npleting the Federal budget for\nsubmission to the Congress in\nJanuary. This is the time for\nfirming up the President's\nlegislative program for the\ncoming session. This is also\nthe time for completing the\nannual State of the Union\nMessage to Congress, the Budg\net Message, the Economic Re\nport. such special messages as\nmay be needed, and generally,\nlaying the foundation for\nmeeting the Nation's problams\nfor the next 12 months.\nIn the meantime, certain\nPresidential duties go right\nalong, of course\u2014as for in\nstance determining the rela\ntionship of the United States\nto the NATO meeting in Paris\na week hence, handling the\nda} -to-day foreign problems of\nour country, processing official\npapers that require the per\nsonal approval of the President,\neither by law or pursuant to\nthe Constitution.\nSo at this time of year, when\nmeet Americans are figuring\nout their Christmas shopping,\nnormally the President and his\nofficial associates are heavily\nengaged in preparing quite dif\nferent kinds of lists and pre\nparing greetings to the Con\ngress that could scarcely go\nunder the heading of Christ\nmas cards or lighthearted wel\ncomes to the new year.\nSo. in such a time, the order\nly functioning of the Govern\nment goes on. The preparatory\nwork incident to the final de\ncisions of the President is the\nresponsibility of the White\nHouse staff and members of\nthe Presidents official family\nAt.no time during this recent\nillness has the President been\nunable to carry out his consti\ntutional duties, or unable to\nmake clear-cut. responsible de\ncisions.\nRecuperative Powers\nI am reminded that in each\nof the President's illnesses, his\nrecuperative powers have as\ntonished his doctors. The latest\noccurrence was no exception.\nYou may recall the doctors'\nreport that the President would\nhave to stay relatively quiet\nand avoid excessive pressure\nand strain for a reasonable\ntime. I don't know what a rea\nsonable time means exactly,\nbut I can certainly tell you\nthis: the night the President\nsustained his latest trouble, he\nwas almost adamant about at\ntending the state dinner he had\narranged for the King of Mo\nrocco. The day afterwards he\nput up a vigorous argument\nabout coming to his office, then\ntalked seriously about holding\na press conference. Falling to\ntape the doctors into either of\nthise ventures, he directed that\nstaff members bring him cer\ntain documents, and this was\ndone.\nThe nex# day. you may recall,\nhe got more heavily Into the\nbusiness of his office. The fol\nlowing day he left the White\nHouse to go to church with\nMrs. Eisenhower. The next day\nhe. drove with Mrs. Elsenhower\nto his Gettysburg (arm. spent\nthe week end there, and made\n.8\n\na number of telephone calls\nto Washington. He drove back\nto Washington last Monday to\nattend a Cabinet meeting, met\nwith his staff on certain pend\ning problems, and the follow\ning two days met with the\n1 leaders of the Congress. On\nThursday he attended a two\ni nour meeting of the National\nSecurity Council.\nWhite House May Limit\nAutos in Motorcades\nThe White House may limit the number of newsmen's cars\nin presidential motorcades because of what happened yesterday.\nThree traffic incidents marred President Eisenhower's au-\ntomobile trip from Gettysburg to Washington. None of them\ninvolved Mr. Elsenhower's own limousine\nBut Press Secretary James C. Hagerty said afterward that\nfor safety's sake, the number\nof cars that follow the Presi\ndent would have to be cut\ndown.\nThere were 15 cars in the\nmotorcade yesterday, including\nthe President's. Normally there\nare half a dozen newsmen's\ncars and three or four White\nHouse cars. The 15 included\nat least live White House cars\nTrip in Rain\nMost of the 85-mile trip was\nmade in rain. The presidential\nlimousine, lead car in the\ncaravan, traveled at the maxi\nmum speed limits most of the\nway.\nIn one of the three incidents\na car carrying four reporters\nwas hit from behind, while It\nwas at a standstill, by an auto\ndriven by a Secret Service\nagent. Damage was slight.\nIn another, a Montgomery\nCounty police cruiser pulled up\nalongside Mr. Eisenhower's\nlimousine The officers told the\nPresident's chauffeur. Deeter\nFlohr, that some of the news\nmen's cars in the tear were\ndriving two abreast, thus\ncreating a traffic hazard. The\nStevenson Opposes Cuts\nToObtain Missile Funds\nNEW YORK. Dec. 10 <JP|.\u2014\nAdlet E. Stevenson has advised\nagainst cutting the domestic\nbudget to finance an accelerated\nmissiles program.\nMr. Stevenson outlined his\nprogragn for catching up with\nRussia in science last night\nbefore the New York County\nLawyers Association.\nHe said the United States\nand Its allies should give new\neconomic help to the weaker\nareas of Asia and Africa to\noutmaneuver the Russians\nthere.\nIt must not be a cautious\napproach. Mr. Stevenson said.'\nbut a. resolute, nonpartisan de\ntermination to lead and stay\non course.\nWants AM Co-ordinated\nHe urged that the North At\nlantic Treaty Organization be\nused not only for Immediate\nmilitary needs in meeting the\nRussian challenge, but for this\nlarger effort In a \u201cJoint search\nfor a better, safer Europe.\u201d\nWhile he strongly favors en\nlarging the foreign aid pro\ngram. Mr. Btevenson said, he\nbelieves It should be co-ordi\nnated with similar programs of\nother free governments.\nIt is up to capitalist democ\nracies. he said, to prove they\ncan do these things without\nsacrificing the essentials of ln-\nKH A.';,: 4' <8\njgPW\nyou can give\nI\nto help him ease tension, fatigue...\nNIAGARA CYCLO-MASSAGE*\nW I\nll fbk\u2019A a wonderful, unique gift that anyone would k i\nwant to receive. Niagara's famous Thermo-Cyclopad*\nis used daily hy thousands of people to help rase ner- gLjJf\nvoua tension and fatigue, soothe tired, sore musclea,\nrelieve pains of arthritis, bursitis, rheumatism to f\naid over-all physical well-being. What more could one\nwant? Actually, Niagara helps you experience the most\nwonderful feeling of well-being you may ever have THItMO .CYCIO.\nknown. PAD Heet-Me\u00bb\u00bb\u00abg\u00ab $\u2022\u00bb.-.inciudei\nGet complete details today on Niagara Cyclo- lo(t tom f O ftobie heat mouoge\nMassage the most thoughtful gift you can ever give pod to on, Me on, or i.on agoimt\nanyone' ...the venotile Hond Unii for local\nised manage and on ottrodive\nSTOP IN TODAY OR SIND COUPON inilrumonl cote.\nNIAGARA\nIN WASHINGTON In A,lin t ton. V, THERMO CYCIOPAD SET j\n720\nW* Sell 8 Service The Public Direct\nA f\nSenate Probers\nStudy UAW Data\nDETROIT. Dec. 10 (>PK\u2014ln\nvestigators for the Senate\nRackets Investigating Commit\ntee are In Detroit to look into\nthe affairs of the United Auto\ni Workers Union.\nJohn McGovern, committee\ncounsel, indicated the. Investi\ngation would Include the\nunion's strike against the Koh\nler Co., the UAW s political ac\ntivities and the 1848 shooting\nof UAW President Walter Reu\nther.\n\"I can't go into details Mr.\nMcGovern said. \"But there are\na number of people I want to\nhave a talk with.\n\"We are going into all phases\nof the union and the activities\nof all the top officers including\nReuther.\u201d\nroad at that point is a four\nlane divided highway.\nIn the third incident. Mr.\nHagerty said, one of the cars\npulled abreast of me cat in\nwhich he and While House\ni Physician Maj. Gen. Howard\nMcC. Snyder were riding. He\nsaid the car almost nicked his.\nIncidents in Outskirts\nAll the incidents occurred on\ni the outskirts of Washington.\n1 They were the first since re\nporters were flagged down sev\neral months ago by Montgom\nery County police and told they\nwere exceeding the speed limit\nOn that occasion they were\ntraveling directly behind the\nPresident's limousine.\nThe President told a news\nconference later that he had\nnot been aware that his car\nwas traveling m excess of the\nlimit. He said he had yisued\niiutructionr to his driver to\navoid exceeding the limit in the\nfuture.\nLast spring a Pennsylvania\nState patrolman tried to hail\npress cars near the President's\nGettysburg farm.\ndividual welfare as the Soviet\nUnion has done.\nUrges Bold Resolution I,\nMr. Btevenson said he has i\nbeen Impressed by American\npreparation for the forthcom- i\nlng NATO conference in Partt.\nAs a special consultant to the i\nState Department, he recently I\nattended conferences in Wash- i\nington at which the preparo-d\ntions were viewed.\n\"The President has acted I\ncreditably, in my judgment, in\ntaking steps to restore urgency\nto our missile program.\" he de-\ndared. \"But there are still\nother military programs that\nmust be faced with bold reso-\nllution.\"\nThese Include providing ade-\nquate mobile forces to cope\n\"with small wars and keep\nthem small.\u201d a drastic reor- t\n1 gamzatlon of the Defense De-\npari merit to eliminate Inter-\ni service conflicts, and an tm\ni proved military recruitment i\nprogram with a pay incentive i\nfor trained specialists to re- r\nmain in service.\n\"It is well to remind our\nselves here In America of the I\nlesson of the satellites\u2014that we t\nare part of the human family\nand must learn to live not only\nwith our allies but our adver- i\nsaries,\" Mr. Stevenson said. i\nThe United States has been l\nTalk Indicates\nPresident Will\nGo to Paris\nBy MARY McGRORY\nSherman Adams' presenta\ntion of President Elsenhower as\na strong man \"back In the\nsaddle\" in a St. Louis speech\nlast night was being read here\ntoday as another indication\nthat the President will go to\nParis.\nThe man who sees the Pres\nident most told a Republican\nfinance dinner that he had left\nbehind him \"a man who looks\nstrong\u2014acts strong\u2014and a\nman who 1s strong.\"\n\"And let's not forget this.\u201d\nsaid the Presidential assistant.\n\"His quick recovery means\nperhaps as much to millions all\nover the world, for they, with\nus. believe deeply in Dwight D\nEisenhower.\"\nMr. Adam's remarks appeared\nto anticipate the outcome of a\nnew medical examination\nscheduled for 2:30 pm today\nto determine Mr Elsenhower\u2019s\nfltness for the Paris trip.\nSpecialists Called In\nMaj. Gen Howard M. Snyder,\nthe President\u2019s personal physi\ncian. called in a team of\nspecialists, including neurolog\nists. to help make the decisive\ncheck on Mr. Eisenhower's\nrecovery.\nWhile House Press Secretary\nJames C. Hagerty said he ex\npected to announce soon after\nthe medical examination and\nconsultation whether the Pres\nident or Vice President Nixon\nwill head the American dele\ngation at the NATO summit\nmeeting.\nThe President, at work In\nhis office at 8:05 am. today,\nconferred for IS minutes later\nIn the morning with Nurl al-\nSald. former Prime Minister of\nIraq.\nThe Iraqi visitor told news\nmen that Mr. Eisenhower ap\npeared to be in excellent health, i\nWith a smile, he then stepped\nover to \"knock on wood\" by\ntouching a large table in the\nWhite House lobby\nMeanwhile, in Mr Adams\nlayman's opinion, the Presi\ndent is well on his way to!\ncomplete recovery and \"in\nexcellent shape\nRays President Is Alert\nThe President himself was\nquoted by Mr Hagerty yester\nday as saying he feels \"okay\"\nafter a long week end of rest j\nat his Gettysburg. Pa., farm.j\nMr Eisenhower went to thej\nfarm last Thursday and re\nturned late yesterday.\nAs if to scotch all talk of j\nany presidential Intention to 1\nresign. Mr. Adams said Mr.\nEisenhower's mind was \"keen,\nalert, vigorous.\u201d and that \"his\ndetermination to advance world\npeace and keep America mili\ntarily. economically and spir\nitually strong is as Arm. as\nintense as it ever was\n\"In short, the President is\nback in the saddle.\" according\nlosing ground in the under\ndeveloped countries of the'\nworld, he declared.\n\"Already. Soviet nonmilitary\nforeign expenditure is pressing\nus closely in amount, and their\neffort is on an ascending curve\nwhile ours is descending\nSuch help, he contended,\nshould be coupled with a closer\nco-operation with other West\nern nations.\n\"There is going to have to be\nsome belt tightening, some\nmore self-sacriflce and some\nmore political courage on both\nsides of the fence,\" he declared.\nBut he deplored suggestions\nthat domestic budgets be cut\nto pay for expanded missiles\ndevelopment.\n\"What program is it that is\nto be cut back?\" he asked. \"Is\nIt education, slum clearance,\nhealth, social security?\"\ni\n_ _ _\nto l lt. Adams. \u201cIda grip on\nthe reina la tight and sure.\u201d\nFurther. Mr. Adams told bis\naudience. \"At no time during\nhis recent Illness has the\nPresident been unable to carry\nout his constitutional duties,\nor unable to make clear-cut\nresponsible decisions.\u201d\nWanted la Reef Active\nMr. Adams also reinforced\nVice President Nixon's \"Cageci\nllon\" Image of the President,\ngiven two days after Mr. Elsen-,\nhower suffered his stroke.\n\"The night the President sus\ntained his latest trouble.\" said\nMr. Adams, \"he was almost ad\namant about attending the\nstate dinner he had arranged\nfor the King of Morocco. The\nday afterward he put up a vig\norous argument about coming\nto his office, then talked seri\nously about holding a press con\nference. Falling to talk the\ndoctors Into either of these ven\ntures. he directed that staff\nmembers bring him certain doc\numents, and this was done. The\nnext day, you may recall, he got\nmore heavily into the business\nof his office.\u201d\nMr. Adams dismissed as\n\"chatter\" reports of either a\nusurpation of power or a strug\ngle for It In the White House.\n\"There has been some chatter\nabout usurpation of powers by\nmyself or others on the Presi\ndents staff. There has been a\ngood deal of misleading clap\n101 l lie\u2019ll OPEN EVENINGS Monday Through Friday\nGive her. a Lifetime of\nMusic this Christmas a\nWUIIITZER\nPIANO\nWhan you select the piano for your child\nthis ChrisNnos, and value and quality ore\nimportont considerations, remember that\nmar# people buy Wurlitser pianos than\nthose of any other name. This leadership\nis vour guarantee of greater value and\nfiner piano quality for your investment.\nSee all the models of this foremost piano\nvolue in our showrooms\nPrivet Hr girl nt f.Vti.OH Easy Terms\nM 13)0 G Street N.W.\n2821 Mt. Vernon Are., Alee.\nKing 8-8886\nMovrt: Wo* 9:159; Set, 9:15 6. Ale., 12 Set ,8 6\njust arrived\nto 'SW- your\nChristmas gift giving\nVaraflame! the world's first\n\n\u201cjet power\"\nlighter... by Ronson\nPress down for the only modern fuel Injection\nIn a lighter. A Jet of Ronson\u2019s new Butron\nvapor fuel ignites Instantaneously, sends up a\nclean-burning, odorless, wickless flame easily\nvaried for cigarette, cigar and pipe lighting.\nThe Varaflame fills without disassembling,\nand the fuel supply lasts for months Like all\nRonson lighters, the Varaflame Is guaranteed\nfor one full year.\nVaraflame lighter In presentation gift box. com\nplete with over a year's supply of Button fuel in\nexrluslve Multi-Fill rylinder.\n*17 50\nSo f rtrrol Tat\nriis\\cmvarK\\\nk. |J &son\nHome ol Flawless Diamonds Since lit V\nJjfelN ISIS F Street\nSdVltiJ Northwest\nyo\u00dfay Sterling